Germany, year zero
May 8th always reminds me of 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was drawing to a close.
My father, a resister, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide after my release from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
This was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have some volumes of romantic poetry picked up from a bookstore.
I was sixteen. The occupation forces were committing every excess.
It was difficult to procure food.
My father was transported directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and charged with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, even if for our family it was clearly a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what?
For what future?
"You must help," my mother said to me.
I offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to several distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Fifty-five days later, I was back in school.
I had a special card as a "victim of fascism," while others wore a Iron Cross obtained for late military service.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their house destroyed by bombings, nearly all mourned the loss of loved ones.
However, this phase did not last.
It is practically incredible, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and especially accompanied by a new form of subjugation.
Camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
On the other hand, after a short period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled strengthening of autonomy.
A year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
The democracy was not a mere empty phrase, and it relied on German traditions.
Indeed, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each wanted to consolidate “their” part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be drawn from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is economic and linked to the Marshall Plan.
Perhaps regrettable, but democracy certainly takes root more easily in an economic recovery context.
To do this, one must above all have initiative, from individuals who wish to end a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (like those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but having some initial capital makes things easier.
Which is why the American support through the Marshall Plan is important.
Similarly, the European Union has helped the formerly communist countries, and continues to accompany them in their journey.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials rendered the guilt of Nazi leaders indubitable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long path by preoccupying itself with the past.
In fact, many have described the years after 1949 under Adenauer as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi figures remained in their positions.
D'une certaine façon, le pays ignorait son passé pour avancer vers l'avenir.
Des années plus tard, après l'établissement d'une économie de marché et d'une démocratie politique, l'Allemagne a fait face à son passé, avec beaucoup de succès.
Le passé nazi est unique dans l'horreur, et les comparaisons avec d'autres pays meurtris prêtent donc à confusion.
Pourtant, à sa façon, la Pologne a suivi un parcours similaire après 1989 : d'abord la nouveauté, puis une tentative d'assumer le passé.
En définitive, c'est une meilleure méthode.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an occasion to look back at the past with sadness and anger, but also to look towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
